<subSubSection id="C307654D8720FFDF46C3A0B164630B75" pageId="4" pageNumber="593" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BA236C68720FFDF46C3A0B164630B75" blockId="4.[151,1437,151,357]" pageId="4" pageNumber="593">
<emphasis id="B969EAD48720FFDF46C3A0B1644B0ADA" bold="true" box="[199,334,151,177]" pageId="4" pageNumber="593">Etymology.</emphasis>
Latin, “ 
<taxonomicName id="4C1D4D458720FFDF47AFA0B167200ADA" authorityName="Heffern &amp; Santos-Silva" authorityYear="2022" box="[427,549,151,177]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Parmakanthion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="593" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="profundum">
<emphasis id="B969EAD48720FFDF47AFA0B167200ADA" box="[427,549,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="593">profundum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
”; allusive to the country of the type-locality. 
<collectingCountry id="F30A76568720FFDF4220A0B161940ADA" box="[1060,1169,151,177]" name="Honduras" pageId="4" pageNumber="593">Honduras</collectingCountry>
was named by Christopher Columbus due to the deep water off the coast of the country. 
<collectingCountry id="F30A76568720FFDF4583A09D66F10ABE" box="[903,1012,187,213]" name="Honduras" pageId="4" pageNumber="593">Honduras</collectingCountry>
is the plural of “ 
<emphasis id="B969EAD48720FFDF42B1A09D60110ABE" box="[1205,1300,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="593">hondura</emphasis>
”, a Spanish word that means depth (“ 
<taxonomicName id="4C1D4D458720FFDF47B2A0F967350A92" authorityName="Heffern &amp; Santos-Silva" authorityYear="2022" box="[438,560,223,249]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Parmakanthion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="593" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="profundum">
<emphasis id="B969EAD48720FFDF47B2A0F967350A92" box="[438,560,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="593">profundum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
” in Latin). Here used as adjective nominative neuter singular of “profundus” (meaning “deep”).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C307654D8720FFDF46C3A10164370B0E" pageId="4" pageNumber="593" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BA236C68720FFDF46C3A10164370B0E" blockId="4.[151,1437,151,357]" pageId="4" pageNumber="593">
<emphasis id="B969EAD48720FFDF46C3A101643E0B2A" bold="true" box="[199,315,295,321]" pageId="4" pageNumber="593">Remarks.</emphasis>
Currently, only two species of Parmenini are known from 
<collectingCountry id="F30A76568720FFDF45C0A10161310B2A" box="[964,1076,295,321]" name="Honduras" pageId="4" pageNumber="593">Honduras</collectingCountry>
, and both belong to 
<taxonomicName id="4C1D4D458720FFDF4316A101642B0B0E" authority="Pascoe, 1862" authorityName="Pascoe" authorityYear="1862" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Echthistatus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="593" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B969EAD48720FFDF4316A10160990B2A" box="[1298,1436,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="593">Echthistatus</emphasis>
Pascoe, 1862
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
